      <article class="aap-article" id="article-workflow-rcm">
        <span class="aap-meta">Revenue Cycle</span>
        <h3>Why revenue-cycle problems are usually workflow problems first</h3>
        <p>When a practice says it has a billing problem, the visible symptom is usually at the end of the chain. A denial shows up. A claim sits too long in A/R. Someone realizes patient responsibility was not communicated clearly. A payer issue seems to be repeating. It is tempting to label all of that as a billing problem because the financial consequence is what hurts first. In reality, many of the most expensive revenue-cycle issues begin much earlier, inside the operating habits of the practice.</p>
        <p>Eligibility is a good example. CMS’s HETS guidance is a reminder that eligibility verification is not an abstract compliance step. It exists to help prepare accurate claims, determine beneficiary liability, and confirm whether a service is covered before the claim ever goes out. In other words, the workflow upstream matters. When eligibility is inconsistent, loosely documented, or handled too late, downstream billing teams are forced to spend time correcting problems that were preventable at intake. That is exactly how administrative work expands while confidence in the numbers goes down.</p>
        <p>The same is true for claim status handling. CMS recommends electronic 276/277 claim status workflows because they reduce manual calls, manual status checks, and manual posting work. The point is not simply that the transaction exists. The point is that a cleaner workflow gives the practice better visibility into what is happening and lowers the amount of labor required just to answer basic questions. Practices that rely too heavily on ad hoc portal checks, disconnected spreadsheets, or memory-based follow-up create their own delay layer. Over time, that delay layer becomes part of the cost structure of the business.</p>
        <p>Administrative simplification is the broader lesson. CMS describes HIPAA standard transactions as a way to standardize how business is done so the industry can automate more of its billing and payment processes, spend less time on administrative work, and reduce cost. That matters for small and mid-sized practices just as much as it does for larger organizations. The practical takeaway is simple: when the workflow is inconsistent, the practice pays for that inconsistency twice. First in rework, then in slower or weaker revenue performance.</p>
        <p>The CAQH Index reinforces the same pattern from a wider industry lens. CAQH continues to show that manual administrative processes still absorb enormous amounts of provider time and that there is substantial room for additional savings when workflows become more electronic and more standardized. For practice leaders, this is not just an argument for more software. It is an argument for better operational design. A bad workflow inside a new tool is still a bad workflow. A cleaner operating model is what lets technology actually create value.</p>
        <p>That is why the strongest RCM support is almost never just about “working denials harder.” It is about looking at intake, eligibility, payer communication, claim status visibility, documentation handoffs, and staff accountability as one connected system. When those handoffs get cleaner, denials become easier to prevent, claim status becomes easier to interpret, and financial performance becomes easier to trust. Revenue-cycle improvement becomes more durable when the practice stops treating billing as a department problem and starts treating it as an operational design problem.</p>

        <div class="aap-sources">
          <h4>Sources</h4>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="https://www.cms.gov/data-research/cms-information-technology/hipaa-eligibility-transaction-system" target="_blank" rel="noopener">CMS: HIPAA Eligibility Transaction System (HETS)</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/electronic-billing/claim-status-request-response" target="_blank" rel="noopener">CMS: Claim Status Request and Response</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.cms.gov/priorities/burden-reduction/overview/administrative-simplification/about-administrative-simplification" target="_blank" rel="noopener">CMS: About Administrative Simplification</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.caqh.org/insights/caqh-index-report" target="_blank" rel="noopener">CAQH: The CAQH Index Report</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="aap-article" id="article-documentation-burden" style="margin-top:24px;">
        <span class="aap-meta">Documentation & Workflow</span>
        <h3>What after-hours charting is really telling you about the practice</h3>
        <p>After-hours charting is often talked about as an individual provider problem, as though the main question is whether someone documents faster or slower than someone else. That framing misses the bigger issue. Persistent documentation drag usually reveals a workflow problem, an implementation problem, or a usability problem that the practice has allowed to become normal.</p>
        <p>The HHS strategy on reducing regulatory and administrative burden related to health IT and EHRs remains useful precisely because it does not pretend documentation burden can be solved through motivation alone. The report addresses clinical documentation, usability, and workflow alignment together. That is the right lens. When documentation requirements are layered awkwardly into the EHR, when templates are inconsistent, when note expectations are unclear, or when the operational purpose of the note keeps shifting, the burden compounds quickly. Providers feel it in time pressure. Administrators feel it in delayed follow-through. Billing feels it in incomplete handoffs and slower claim readiness.</p>
        <p>The report also points toward something practice leaders often underestimate: implementation decisions matter. It is not enough to purchase a system with broad capability. The way the system is configured, the way documentation expectations are trained, and the way data is reused across the workflow all shape whether the documentation process feels supportive or exhausting. A practice can have strong software and still create a poor documentation environment if its internal decisions are fragmented.</p>
        <p>That matters operationally because documentation burden rarely stays isolated. It spills into schedule pressure, provider frustration, lagging billing steps, and weaker visibility into what has or has not been completed. In behavioral health practices especially, where documentation quality, timeliness, and consistency often intersect directly with reimbursement and payer scrutiny, the cost of a messy documentation process is not only emotional. It becomes administrative and financial as well.</p>
        <p>A better approach starts by treating documentation as part of workflow design rather than as a compliance chore appended to the end of care. Teams need clearer note expectations, better template discipline, more usable handoffs, and more realistic review steps. Not every field should be doing equal work. Not every provider should be inventing their own structure from scratch. And not every burden should be solved by asking clinicians to simply “be more efficient.”</p>
        <p>The strongest documentation improvements tend to come from a combination of standardization and restraint. Standardization creates consistency where it matters. Restraint prevents the practice from overbuilding notes, overcomplicating templates, or using the EHR as a catch-all repository for every internal anxiety. When the documentation workflow is cleaner, the gain is bigger than time savings alone. The entire practice becomes easier to run because less energy is spent compensating for a system that never fit real care delivery in the first place.</p>

        <div class="aap-sources">
          <h4>Sources</h4>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="https://healthit.gov/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/BurdenReport.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">HHS / ONC / CMS: Strategy on Reducing Regulatory and Administrative Burden Relating to the Use of Health IT and EHRs</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.healthit.gov/news/2020/2/21/final-report-delivers-strategy-reduce-ehr-burden" target="_blank" rel="noopener">HealthIT.gov: Final Report Delivers a Strategy to Reduce EHR Burden</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="aap-article" id="article-practical-ai" style="margin-top:24px;">
        <span class="aap-meta">Practical AI</span>
        <h3>What practical AI implementation should actually look like in healthcare</h3>
        <p>Most healthcare teams do not need another sweeping claim that AI will “transform everything.” They need a sober way to decide where automation can reduce administrative burden, where review has to stay in place, and how to implement tools without weakening trust in the underlying workflow. That is why practical AI implementation matters more than AI enthusiasm.</p>
        <p>NIST’s AI Risk Management Framework is useful here because it shifts the conversation away from hype and toward governance, documentation, and risk management. The framework is not healthcare-specific, but its central discipline translates well to healthcare operations: understand the use case clearly, document how the system is being used, identify where risk sits, define oversight, and manage the process rather than assuming the tool will manage itself. For practices evaluating AI in documentation, intake support, routing, or revenue-cycle operations, that is the right starting posture.</p>
        <p>NIST’s generative AI profile adds another important layer. Generative systems create distinct risks around reliability, explainability, and output quality. In healthcare, those risks become especially relevant when teams start applying AI to notes, summaries, administrative messaging, or workflow support. The practical question is not whether AI can generate output. It can. The practical question is whether the practice has a disciplined way to review that output, constrain its use, and define where human judgment remains mandatory.</p>
        <p>That is why the most useful healthcare AI implementations tend to be narrower than the marketing promises. AI can help reduce repetitive administrative work, support draft creation, improve workflow routing, or surface missing information earlier in the process. Those are meaningful wins. But they only remain wins when the workflow around the tool is clean. If the practice has no clear owner for review, no documentation discipline, no quality checks, or no defined limits on use, the tool becomes another source of inconsistency rather than a source of relief.</p>
        <p>Healthcare teams also need to keep implementation grounded in current-system reality. A workable AI deployment should fit the existing workflow where possible, respect privacy and security obligations, and avoid creating parallel processes that staff will not reliably follow. This is where many AI rollouts go wrong. They are launched as isolated features instead of being integrated into the actual operating model of the practice. Adoption weakens, exceptions multiply, and the team ends up carrying more complexity instead of less.</p>
        <p>Practical AI is not anti-innovation. It is disciplined innovation. It asks better questions at the beginning: What problem are we actually solving? What part of the workflow improves if this works? Who reviews output? What gets documented? What should never be automated away? Those questions lead to better decisions than a general promise of efficiency. In healthcare operations, the practices that benefit most from AI are usually the ones that treat governance, workflow design, and implementation support as part of the product, not as afterthoughts.</p>

        <div class="aap-sources">
          <h4>Sources</h4>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="https://www.nist.gov/itl/ai-risk-management-framework" target="_blank" rel="noopener">NIST: AI Risk Management Framework</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.nist.gov/itl/ai-risk-management-framework/ai-risk-management-framework-resources" target="_blank" rel="noopener">NIST: AI Risk Management Framework Resources</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://healthit.gov/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/BurdenReport.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">HHS / ONC / CMS: Strategy on Reducing Regulatory and Administrative Burden Relating to the Use of Health IT and EHRs</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

